{"nodes":[{"content":"Animations overview","pos":[75,94]},{"content":"Use the animations from the Windows Runtime animation library to integrate the Windows look and feel into your app.","pos":[108,223]},{"content":"Animations overview","pos":[230,249]},{"content":"Updated for UWP apps on Windows 10.","pos":[254,289]},{"content":"For Windows 8.x articles, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>archive<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619132)</ept>","pos":[290,382]},{"content":"Animations in the Windows Runtime can enhance your app by adding movement and interactivity.","pos":[388,480]},{"content":"By using the animations from the Windows Runtime animation library, you can integrate the Windows look and feel into your app.","pos":[481,607]},{"content":"This topic provides a summary of the animations and examples of typical scenarios where each is used.","pos":[608,709]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Tip<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  The Windows Runtime controls for XAML include certain types of animations as built-in behaviors that come from an animation library.","pos":[711,852]},{"content":"By using these controls in your app, you can get the animated look and feel without having to program it yourself.","pos":[853,967]},{"content":"Animations from the Windows Runtime animation library provide these benefits:","pos":[969,1046]},{"pos":[1052,1163],"content":"Motions that align to the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Guidelines for animations<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Dn611854)</ept>"},{"content":"Fast, fluid transitions between UI states that inform but do not distract the user","pos":[1168,1250]},{"content":"Visual behavior that indicates transitions within an app to the user","pos":[1255,1323]},{"content":"For example, when the user adds an item to a list, instead of the new item instantly appearing in the list, the new item animates into place.","pos":[1325,1466]},{"content":"The other items in the list animate to their new positions over a short period of time, making room for the added item.","pos":[1467,1586]},{"content":"The transition behavior here makes the control interaction more apparent to the user.","pos":[1587,1672]},{"content":"The animation library does not provide animations for every possible scenario.","pos":[1674,1752]},{"content":"There are cases where you might wish to create a custom animation in XAML.","pos":[1753,1827]},{"content":"For more info, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Storyboarded animations<ept id=\"p1\">](storyboarded-animations.md)</ept>.","pos":[1828,1901]},{"content":"Additionally, for certain advanced scenarios like animating an item based on scroll position of a ScrollViewer, developers may wish to use Visual Layer interoperation to implement custom animations.","pos":[1903,2101]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Visual Layer<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/uwp/graphics/visual-layer)</ept> for more information.","pos":[2102,2210]},{"content":"Types of animations","pos":[2215,2234]},{"content":"The Windows Runtime animation system and the animation library serve the larger goal of enabling controls and other parts of UI to have an animated behavior.","pos":[2236,2393]},{"content":"There are several distinct types of animations.","pos":[2394,2441]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Theme transitions<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> are applied automatically when certain conditions change in the UI, involving controls or elements from the predefined Windows Runtime XAML UI types.","pos":[2447,2616]},{"content":"These are termed <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>theme transitions<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> because the animations support the Windows look and feel, and define what all apps do for particular UI scenarios when they change from one interaction mode to another.","pos":[2617,2822]},{"content":"The theme transitions are part of the animation library.","pos":[2823,2879]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Theme animations<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> are animations to one or more properties of predefined Windows Runtime XAML UI types.","pos":[2884,2988]},{"content":"Theme animations differ from theme transitions because theme animations target one specific element and exist in specific visual states within a control, whereas the theme transitions are assigned to properties of the control that exist outside of the visual states and influence the transitions between those states.","pos":[2989,3306]},{"content":"Many of the Windows Runtime XAML controls include theme animations within storyboards that are part of their control template, with the animations triggered by visual states.","pos":[3307,3481]},{"content":"So long as you're not modifying the templates, you'll have those built-in theme animations available for the controls in your UI.","pos":[3482,3611]},{"content":"However, if you do replace templates, then you'll be removing the built-in control theme animations too.","pos":[3612,3716]},{"content":"To get them back, you must define a storyboard that includes theme animations within the control's set of visual states.","pos":[3717,3837]},{"content":"You can also run theme animations from storyboards that aren't within visual states and start them with the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Begin<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210491)</ept> method, but that's less common.","pos":[3838,4047]},{"content":"Theme animations are part of the animation library.","pos":[4048,4099]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Visual transitions<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> are applied when a control transitions from one of its defined visual states to another state.","pos":[4104,4219]},{"content":"These are custom animations that you write, and are typically related to the custom template you write for a control and the visual state definitions within that template.","pos":[4220,4391]},{"content":"The animation only runs during the time between states, and that's typically a short amount of time, a few seconds at most.","pos":[4392,4515]},{"content":"For more info, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>\"VisualTransition\" section of Storyboarded animations for visual states<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/JJ819808#VisualTransition)</ept>.","pos":[4516,4689]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Storyboarded animations<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> animate the value of a Windows Runtime dependency property over time.","pos":[4694,4789]},{"content":"Storyboards can be defined as part of a visual transition, or triggered at runtime by the application.","pos":[4790,4892]},{"content":"For more info, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Storyboarded animations<ept id=\"p1\">](storyboarded-animations.md)</ept>.","pos":[4893,4966]},{"content":"For more info about dependency properties and where they exist, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Dependency properties overview<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt185583)</ept>.","pos":[4967,5126]},{"content":"Animations available in the library","pos":[5131,5166]},{"content":"The following animations are supplied in the animation library.","pos":[5168,5231]},{"content":"Click on the name of an animation to learn more about their main usage scenarios, how to define them, and to see an example of the animation.","pos":[5232,5373]},{"pos":[5379,5541],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Page transition<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#page-transition)</ept>: Animates page transitions in a <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Frame<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242682)</ept>."},{"pos":[5546,5707],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Content and entrance transition<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#content-transition-and-entrance-transition)</ept>: Animates one piece or set of content into or out of view."},{"pos":[5712,5860],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Fade in/out, and crossfade<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#fade-in-out-and-crossfade)</ept>: Shows transient elements or controls, or refreshes a content area."},{"pos":[5865,5976],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Pointer up/down<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#pointer-up-down)</ept>: Gives visual feedback of a tap or click on a tile."},{"pos":[5981,6069],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Reposition<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#reposition)</ept>: Moves an element into a new position."},{"pos":[6074,6177],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Show/hide popup<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#show-hide-popup)</ept>: Displays contextual UI on top of the view."},{"pos":[6182,6325],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Show/hide edge UI<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#show-hide-edge-ui)</ept>: Slides edge-based UI, including large UI such as a panel, into or out of view."},{"pos":[6330,6459],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>List item changes<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#list-item-changes)</ept>: Adds or deletes an item from a list, or reordering of the items."},{"pos":[6464,6568],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Drag/drop<ept id=\"p1\">](./animations-overview.md#drag-drop)</ept>: Gives visual feedback during a drag-and-drop operation."},{"content":"Page transition","pos":[6574,6589]},{"content":"Use page transitions to animate navigation within an app.","pos":[6591,6648]},{"content":"Since almost all apps use some kind of navigation, page transition animations are the most common type of theme animation used by apps.","pos":[6649,6784]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>NavigationThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/apps/windows.ui.xaml.media.animation. Therenavigationthemetransition)</ept> for more information about the page transition APIs.","pos":[6785,6992]},{"content":"Content transition and entrance transition","pos":[7000,7042]},{"content":"Use content transition animations (<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ContentThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243103)</ept>) to move a piece or a set of content into or out of the current view.","pos":[7044,7235]},{"content":"For example, the content transition animations show content that was not ready to display when the page was first loaded, or when the content changes on a section of a page.","pos":[7236,7409]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>EntranceThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210288)</ept> represents a motion that can apply to content when a page or large section of UI is first loaded.","pos":[7411,7596]},{"content":"Thus the first appearance of content can offer different feedback than a change to content does.","pos":[7597,7693]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>EntranceThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210288)</ept> is equivalent to a <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>NavigationThemeTransition<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/apps/windows.ui.xaml.media.animation.navigationthemetransition)</ept> with the default parameters, but may be used outside of a <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>Frame<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242682)</ept>.","pos":[7694,8074]},{"content":"Fade in/out, and crossfade","pos":[8084,8110]},{"content":"Use fade in and fade out animations to show or hide transient UI or controls.","pos":[8112,8189]},{"content":"In XAML these are represented as <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>FadeInThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210298)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>FadeOutThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210302)</ept>.","pos":[8190,8398]},{"content":"One example is in an app bar in which new controls can appear due to user interaction.","pos":[8399,8485]},{"content":"Another example is a transient scroll bar or panning indicator that is faded out after no user input has been detected for some amount of time.","pos":[8486,8629]},{"content":"Apps should also use the fade in animation when they transition from a placeholder item to the final item as content loads dynamically.","pos":[8630,8765]},{"content":"Use a crossfade animation to smooth the transition when an item's state is changing; for example, when the app refreshes the current contents of a view.","pos":[8767,8919]},{"content":"The XAML animation library does not supply a dedicated crossfade animation (no equivalent for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>crossFade<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR212661)</ept>), but you can achieve the same result using <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>FadeInThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210298)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>FadeOutThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210302)</ept> with overlapped timing.","pos":[8920,9330]},{"content":"Pointer up/down","pos":[9336,9351]},{"content":"Use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PointerUpThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh969168)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>PointerDownThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh969164)</ept> animations to give the user feedback for a successful tap or click on a tile.","pos":[9353,9620]},{"content":"For example, when a user clicks or taps down on a tile, the pointer down animation is played.","pos":[9621,9714]},{"content":"Once the click or tap has been released, the pointer up animation is played.","pos":[9715,9791]},{"content":"Reposition","pos":[9797,9807]},{"content":"Use the reposition animations (<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>RepositionThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210421)</ept> or <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>RepositionThemeTransition<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210429)</ept>) to move an element into a new position.","pos":[9809,10062]},{"content":"For example, moving the headers in an items control uses the reposition animation.","pos":[10063,10145]},{"content":"Show/hide popup","pos":[10151,10166]},{"content":"Use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PopInThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210383)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>PopOutThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210391)</ept> when you show and hide a <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>Popup<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR227842)</ept> or similar contextual UI on top of the current view.","pos":[10168,10496]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PopupThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh969172)</ept> is a theme transition that's useful feedback if you want to light dismiss a popup.","pos":[10497,10664]},{"content":"Show/hide edge UI","pos":[10670,10687]},{"content":"Use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>EdgeUIThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh702324)</ept> animation to slide small, edge-based UI into and out of view.","pos":[10689,10844]},{"content":"For example, use these animations when you show a custom app bar at the top or bottom of the screen or a UI surface for errors and warnings at the top of the screen.","pos":[10845,11010]},{"content":"Use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PaneThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh969160)</ept> animation to show and hide a pane or panel.","pos":[11012,11147]},{"content":"This is for large edge-based UI such as a custom keyboard or a task pane.","pos":[11148,11221]},{"content":"List item changes","pos":[11227,11244]},{"content":"Use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>AddDeleteThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243047)</ept> animation to add animated behavior when you add or delete an item in an existing list.","pos":[11246,11429]},{"content":"For add, the transition will first reposition existing items in the list to make space for the new items, and then add the new items.","pos":[11430,11563]},{"content":"For delete, the transition removes items from a list and, if necessary, repositions the remaining list items once the deleted items have been removed.","pos":[11564,11714]},{"content":"There's also a separate <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ReorderThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210409)</ept> that you apply if an item changes position in a list.","pos":[11716,11880]},{"content":"This is animated differently than deleting an item and adding it in a new place with the associated delete/add animations.","pos":[11881,12003]},{"pos":[12005,12372],"content":"Note that these animations are included in the default <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ListView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/windows.ui.xaml.controls.listview.aspx)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>GridView<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/windows.ui.xaml.controls.gridview.aspx)</ept> templates so you do not need to manually add these animations if you are already using these controls."},{"content":"Drag/drop","pos":[12378,12387]},{"pos":[12389,12765],"content":"Use the drag animations (<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DragItemThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243173)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>DragOverThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243177)</ept>) and drop animation (<bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>DropTargetItemThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR243185)</ept>) to give visual feedback when the user drags or drops an item."},{"content":"When active, the animations show the user that the list can be rearranged around a dropped item.","pos":[12767,12863]},{"content":"It is helpful for users to know where the item will be placed in a list if it is dropped at the current location.","pos":[12864,12977]},{"content":"The animations give visual feedback that an item being dragged can be dropped between two other items in the list and that those items will move out of the way.","pos":[12978,13138]},{"content":"Using animations with custom controls","pos":[13143,13180]},{"content":"The following table summarizes our recommendations for which animation you should use when you create a custom version of these Windows Runtime controls:","pos":[13182,13335]},{"content":"UI type","pos":[13339,13346]},{"content":"Recommended animation","pos":[13349,13370]},{"content":"Dialog box","pos":[13411,13421]},{