4465,14486]},{"content":"Task pane or edge-based panel","pos":[14619,14648]},{"content":"PaneThemeTransition","pos":[14654,14673]},{"content":"Contents of any UI container","pos":[14802,14830]},{"content":"ContentThemeTransition","pos":[14836,14858]},{"content":"For controls or if no other animation applies","pos":[14993,15038]},{"pos":[15041,15291],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>FadeInThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/apps/windows.ui.xaml.media.animation.fadeinthemeanimation.fadeinthemeanimation.aspx)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>FadeOutThemeAnimation<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210302)</ept>"},{"content":"Transition animation examples","pos":[15301,15330]},{"content":"Ideally, your app uses animations to enhance the user interface or to make it more attractive without annoying your users.","pos":[15332,15454]},{"content":"One way you can do this is to apply animated transitions to UI so that when something enters or leaves the screen or otherwise changes, the animation draws the attention of the user to the change.","pos":[15455,15651]},{"content":"For example, your buttons may rapidly fade in and out of view rather than just appear and disappear.","pos":[15652,15752]},{"content":"We created a number of APIs that can be used to create recommended or typical animation transitions that are consistent.","pos":[15753,15873]},{"content":"The example here shows how to apply an animation to a button so that it swiftly slides into view.","pos":[15874,15971]},{"content":"In this code, we add the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>EntranceThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210288)</ept> object to the transition collection of the button.","pos":[16196,16359]},{"content":"Now, when the button is first rendered, it swiftly slides into view rather than just appear.","pos":[16360,16452]},{"content":"You can set a few properties on the animation object in order to adjust how far it slides and from what direction, but it's really meant to be a simple API for a specific scenario, that is, to make an eye-catching entrance.","pos":[16453,16676]},{"content":"You can also define transition animation themes in the style resources of your app, allowing you to apply the effect uniformly.","pos":[16678,16805]},{"content":"This example is equivalent to the previous one, only it is applied using a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Style<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR208849)</ept>:","pos":[16806,16951]},{"content":"The previous examples apply a theme transition to an individual control, however, theme transitions are even more interesting when you apply them to a container of objects.","pos":[17475,17647]},{"content":"When you do this, all the child objects of the container take part in the transition.","pos":[17648,17733]},{"content":"In the following example, an <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>EntranceThemeTransition<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR210288)</ept> is applied to a <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Grid<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242704)</ept> of rectangles.","pos":[17734,17950]},{"pos":[19534,19805],"content":"The child rectangles of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Grid<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242704)</ept> transition into view one after the other in a visually pleasing way rather than all at once as would be the case if you applied this animation to the rectangles individually."},{"content":"Here's a video that demonstrates this animation:","pos":[19807,19855]},{"content":"Animation showing 